For God's sake, keep it down. They're about to&nbsp; reveal the Number One AI Video Generator. &nbsp;&nbsp; This year's updates to the leading AI video models&nbsp; have spoiled me to the point where I no longer&nbsp;&nbsp; expect things to just be "good enough for AI" .&nbsp; I want the best results money can buy. I want&nbsp;&nbsp; my footage to be so realistic that it makes&nbsp; people laugh, cry, or feel genuine fear. I&nbsp;&nbsp; want as little "AI look" in my AI as possible. Let's&nbsp; see which video model can actually deliver that.&nbsp;&nbsp; I tested four models that have either been updated&nbsp; or have just emerged on the scene over the last three&nbsp; months. Seedance 2.0, Kling 3.0, the new kid on&nbsp; the block - Happy Horse, and the very recently&nbsp;&nbsp; released Veo 4 Omni. But I'll tell you more about&nbsp; Veo 4 in the second part of this video. All scenes&nbsp;&nbsp; were shot using the image-to-video method or&nbsp; the Omni function. Every shot was generated&nbsp;&nbsp; on the Imagine.art platform, the sponsor&nbsp; of this video, except for the Veo 4 Omni footage -&nbsp;&nbsp; this model would soon be integrated into&nbsp; the platform as well. The rules were simple:&nbsp;&nbsp; the exact same prompts with a maximum of two&nbsp; generations per model. I decided to crown a winner&nbsp;&nbsp; across five categories: Best acting performance,&nbsp; Best lip-sync performance, Best micro-expressions,&nbsp;&nbsp; Best prompt adherence, and Best physics. Grab&nbsp; your coffee and let's see who takes the crown&nbsp;&nbsp; in each category. Prompt adherence. The more&nbsp; complex the camera movement we request, the&nbsp;&nbsp; more difficult it is for these models to follow&nbsp; our intentions precisely. Here's a clear example. Seedance executed our exact prompt&nbsp; instructions. Others not so much.&nbsp;&nbsp; Acting. Here's an emotionally intense scene that&nbsp; showcases some truly exceptional acting nuance. It doesn't hurt that you left. It hurts&nbsp; that you practiced that face for years. It doesn't hurt that you left. It hurts&nbsp; that you practiced that face for years. It doesn't hurt that you left. It hurts&nbsp; that you practiced that face for years. It doesn't hurt that you left. It hurts&nbsp; that you practiced that face for years. And the award goes to Kling. What really caught&nbsp; my attention was the nervous blinking of her&nbsp;&nbsp; eyes and the incredibly realistic hand physics&nbsp; when she missed her intended grip and grace the&nbsp;&nbsp; table on the descent. Great lip sync, by the way.&nbsp; Acting. This scene not only highlights the acting&nbsp;&nbsp; performance, but also stress tests the model's&nbsp; ability to handle complex mirror reflections. You don't have to finish it.&nbsp; There won't be a wedding.    The dress doesn't know you're afraid. It's not fear. You don't have to finish it. There won't be a&nbsp; wedding. The dress doesn't know you're afraid.&nbsp;&nbsp; It's not fear. In that case, stand up straight.&nbsp; Fear and shame always hunt a person the same way. You don't have to finish it. There won't be a&nbsp; wedding. The dress doesn't know you're afraid.&nbsp;&nbsp; Unfraid. It's not fear. In case fear and shame&nbsp; always hunch a person the same way. You don't&nbsp;&nbsp; have to finish it. There won't be a wedding. The&nbsp; dress doesn't know you're afraid. It's not fear.&nbsp;&nbsp; In that case, stand up straight. Fear and shame&nbsp; always hunch a person the same way. &nbsp; This time, the award goes to Seedance. I especially appreciated&nbsp; how the tailor addresses the bride's reflection&nbsp;&nbsp; in the mirror instead of looking at her directly.&nbsp; It's a beautifully cinematic sequence. &nbsp;&nbsp; Lip-sync. We created this next scene specifically to test&nbsp; dialogue lip- ync.  Was this the worst wedding in&nbsp; the history of this hotel? But the first one where&nbsp; the bride left with the photographer. At least the&nbsp;&nbsp; photos will be honest. You're still laughing.&nbsp; Was this the worst wedding in the history of&nbsp;&nbsp; this hotel? No, but the first one where the bride&nbsp; left with the photographer. At least the photos&nbsp;&nbsp; will be honest. You're still laughing. That's&nbsp; good.   Was this the worst wedding in the history&nbsp;&nbsp;of this hotel? No, but the first one where the&nbsp; bride left with the photographer. At least the&nbsp;&nbsp; photos will be honest. You're still laughing.&nbsp; That's good. &nbsp;&nbsp; Was this the worst wedding in the history of this hotel? No. But the first one where&nbsp;the bride left with the photographer. At least&nbsp;&nbsp; the photos will be honest. You're still laughing.&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; The the top spot for lips-sync goes to Seedance followed by Veo 4 Omni.  &nbsp; Micro-Expressions. Now let's&nbsp; focus on the Holy Grail of screen acting:  these little face muscle or eyes movements that can&nbsp; tell us so much if performed with finesse. Both Veo and Kling failed to follow the&nbsp; prompt as the soldier was supposed to refrain&nbsp; from firing his weapon after a brief&nbsp; moment of hesitation. Seedance nailed it&nbsp;perfectly.  Micro-expressions. You need to focus&nbsp; on that short moment when a politician is being&nbsp;&nbsp; asked a tough question and has to make a quick&nbsp; decision whether to tell the truth or lie. &nbsp; Did you authorize the transfer before the report was&nbsp; buried? That is a completely false accusation.&nbsp;&nbsp; Did you authorize the transfer&nbsp; before the report was buried? That is a completely false accusation.&nbsp; Did you authorize the transfer before&nbsp;the report was buried? That is&nbsp; a completely false accusation.&nbsp;&nbsp; Did you authorize the transfer&nbsp; before the report was buried? That is a completely false accusation.  The&nbsp;award goes to Seedance again. This time we&nbsp;had to use Veo 3.1 as the policy filters in&nbsp;Veo 4 Omni didn't allow us to generate this&nbsp;scene.  Physics. Now on to physics. Which&nbsp;model delivers the most realistic motion? The win goes to Seedance once again for the most&nbsp; realistic performance in my opinion.&nbsp;&nbsp; Physics. We decided to stage a kung-fu fight scene&nbsp; with a...little twist. I hope you'll enjoy it. As you probably noticed, Veo 4 Omni took this pillow&nbsp; fight a tad too seriously. In my opinion, Seedance&nbsp;wins this round.  All right, let's let the dust&nbsp;settle, take a deep breath, and process everything&nbsp;&nbsp; we just witnessed. A few quick clarifications are&nbsp; in order. First of all, Veo 4 Omni is the only model&nbsp;&nbsp; in this shootout limited strictly to 10 seconds&nbsp; shot, whereas the other contenders offer up&nbsp;&nbsp; to 15 seconds of duration. While 10 seconds is&nbsp; still better than 8 seconds we had with Veo 3.1&nbsp;&nbsp; and might be perfectly fine for a TikTok clip,&nbsp; it gives any film director or editor a massive&nbsp;&nbsp; headache when pacing a proper narrative film. But&nbsp; honestly, I don't care what technical constraints&nbsp;&nbsp; Veo might have for capping clips at 10 seconds, and&nbsp; I certainly wasn't going to bottleneck the other&nbsp;&nbsp; models just to level the playing field for them.&nbsp; Secondly, as always, we allowed only one or two&nbsp;&nbsp; generation attempts uh per scene for each model.&nbsp; The prompts were specific and detailed enough that&nbsp;&nbsp; a mature model should deliver exactly what we&nbsp; wanted without forcing us to develop calluses&nbsp;&nbsp; from spamming the "generate" button. Last but not&nbsp; least, I'm a huge advocate for hybrid workflows.&nbsp;&nbsp; You should absolutely deploy a high-end, more&nbsp; expensive model for your critical narrative&nbsp;&nbsp; moments like close-up dialogue or a subtle micro&nbsp; expressions and then jump to a different engine&nbsp;&nbsp; for, say, a wide-angle car chase sequence. Sometimes&nbsp; the choice is driven by budget constraints. Other&nbsp;&nbsp; times, a specific model is simply better suited for&nbsp; a particular type of shot physics. All right. So,&nbsp;&nbsp; which model gets our official stamp of approval?&nbsp; If we are focusing strictly on raw quality&nbsp;&nbsp; regardless of the cost, the definitive winner&nbsp; is Seedance 2.0. Seedance is relatively expensive&nbsp;&nbsp; to operate and has its fair share of quirks, but&nbsp; in my opinion, it remains the gold standard. Kling&nbsp;&nbsp; 3.0 clearly had problems with following&nbsp; complex prompts and with lip-sync, although I liked&nbsp;&nbsp; the acting scene very much. Happy Horse offers the&nbsp; aesthetics I just don't like. It's too "AI plastic"&nbsp;&nbsp; and smoothed out. Now, let's talk about Veo 4 Omni&nbsp; released just a few days ago. First of all,&nbsp;&nbsp; the improvement over 3.1 version is visible.&nbsp; The overall aesthetics are much better. The&nbsp;&nbsp; acting has improved and it's pretty good, too.&nbsp; Two issues we spotted which are actually quite&nbsp;&nbsp; serious. Veo 4 on many occasions had a problem&nbsp; with lip-sync and also didn't follow the prompt,&nbsp;&nbsp; especially when we asked for slightly more&nbsp; complex camera motion. One thing worth noting:&nbsp;&nbsp; the Omni function here is much more than just a&nbsp; chance to use reference items. Veo 4 Omni offers a&nbsp;&nbsp; lot of additional editing functionalities like&nbsp; iterative video editing with preserved content,&nbsp;&nbsp; video remixing or conversational videography&nbsp; direction. But at the end of the day, it all comes&nbsp;&nbsp; down to how good the outcome is, not how easy it&nbsp; was to produce. As the audience doesn't care much&nbsp;&nbsp; about the process, they care about the result. And&nbsp; at least for now, nothing beats Seedance 2.0 &nbsp;&nbsp; in this department. Some news for you. While&nbsp; we were producing this video, Imagine Art, the&nbsp;&nbsp; platform we used to generate most of the today's&nbsp; footage, dropped an interesting new feature called&nbsp;&nbsp; Film Studio. We managed to grab early access and&nbsp; after spending some time playing around in this&nbsp;&nbsp; new environment, I think you should try it too.&nbsp; Film Studio provides intuitive high-speed controls&nbsp;&nbsp; designed to streamline the entire cinematic&nbsp; pipeline. It allows you to select specific camera&nbsp;&nbsp; bodies, focal lengths, camera movements, timing,&nbsp; depth of field, and reference assets natively,&nbsp;&nbsp; completely removing the need to overdescribe&nbsp; these technical parameters in your text prompt.&nbsp;&nbsp; We are going to give it a proper run and&nbsp; shoot an entire upcoming project inside this&nbsp;&nbsp; environment and I'll break down both the final&nbsp; results and the complete workflow in a future&nbsp;&nbsp; video. If you found this shootout insightful&nbsp; or entertaining, please hit like, subscribe,&nbsp;&nbsp; and turn on the notification bell so you don't&nbsp; miss that upcoming breakdown. See you next time!


